default5
default.12
default              
defaultIn the 
defaultwest countrydefault, buses always ran late along one urban corridor, highlighted in a 
defaultBBC Radio Four programme,default File on Fourdefault, on Tuesday 09 August 2005; BBC researchers and presenter(s) lacked inside knowledge to 
defaultsee
default what was really going on, nor to see how the local authority had been duped into premature and un-necessary spend on road improvements.  No matter what the Local Authority was persuaded to do, and did, buses continually ran late, even with bus priority measures.  
defaultI have the programme’s transcript.default  
defaultFile on Four
default is a recorded programme and did not have an imminent editorial deadline to meet.  
default5
default.12.1
default              
defaultThe truth was simpler: the bus operator was running the service with one vehicle LESS than the service frequency and RTRT - 
defaultround trip running timedefault - demanded.  The maximum number of buses a route requires is called the PVR – 
defaultPeak Vehicle Requirementdefault –
default determined from the time taken at the busiest period for a single vehicle to start from its origin point, ready to pick up its first passengers, reach its destination and alight all its passengers, take a ‘
defaultturnround
default time’ break and make the return service journey and be ready 
defaultfor
default its next journey.  Dividing the RTRT by the 
defaultheadwaydefault (
defaultfrequency of service to be provided
default) gives the number of vehicles required.  Thus a 40 minute RTRT and a 10 minute headway requires FOUR buses; a sixty seven minute RTRT on a five minute headway requires 13.4 buses…  ‘Point four’ of a bus is impossible, therefore fourteen vehicles are needed to run the route, by extending the standing time at one or both ends of the route.  
default5
default.12.2
default              
defaultHowever, if a bus operator cannot or will not provide the missing ‘point six’, the route m
defaultight
default still run with thirteen buses, despite submitting a full schedule to the Traffic Commissioners and/or Local Authority.  The service runs 
defaultincreasingly 
defaultlate as the 
defaultday progresses; the 
defaultoperator 
defaulthas to
default cancel at least one round trip later to avoid paying drivers overtime rates for late running.  
default5
default.12.3
default              
default ‘Inside information’ would have told the BBC this – it 
defaultopted
default not to question, not to ask for an external verification of the operator’s claims and to broadcast material as it was given.  The lack of inside information, the skills and knowledge of transport workers, will continue to allow distortion of facts, and keep false impressions vibrant.  
defaultTransport operators deliberately suppress knowledgedefault.
