default‘
defaultScheduling and operating constraintsdefault’: 
default6
default.1
default              
defaultAn operator only has so many buses and trains.  On the railways, train operations are determined by the franchise; on the roads, vehicles are numbered by the likelihood of a profit from fares along the route network or subsidy from a relevant authority.  In both cases, scheduling efficiency determines advantageous uses of equipment.  In both modern cases, the transport supplier’s operating desires come ahead of passengers’ needs.
default6
default.2
default              
defaultIn major centres, bus route patterns and service 
defaultlevels
default 
defaultmay be
default determined (
defaultLondon in particular, Newcastle is set to follow
default) by a route contracts regime.  Beyond these centres, bus operators since national ‘deregulation’ (
defaultexcept London
default) in 1986
default may operate where and when they wish
default.  
defaultBefore
default 1986, regional Traffic Commissioners control bus service
default level
defaults.  The emphasis switched from serving a passenger need to operating only 
defaultwhere
default positive net revenue
defaults might be found
default.
