default.6
default              
defaultOne 
defaulturban 
defaultexample of an over-generous schedule was a
defaultn
default East London trunk route, which on the successful TfL tender required ‘X’ vehicles.  Investigations later revealed that the route was 
defaultrun
default with ‘X-minus-1’ buses.  The route at one end terminated inside its home garage; as a 
defaultgiven
default bus arrived ex-passenger service, it would be left ready for the next departure, having been fully fuelled at the start of the day.  Garage staff removed the arriving ‘running number’ (
defaultthe identity of that day’s combination of trips
default) and installed the next available number in the route sequence.  On paper, this was the full ‘X’ allocation of buses; the turn-round time inside the garage hid the identity swap and enabled the true ‘X-minus-1’ operation.  
default6.6.1
default              
defaultIn London the density of population and generous location of intelligent eyes uncovered this, but in outlying areas, where fewer people 
defaultexist
default to detect this, public purse costs will accumulate.  
